  "reason_thou": "1. Understanding the Issue:\nThe crash occurs in
BoUpSLP::BlockScheduling::extendSchedulingRegion when extending the
scheduling region 'end' side. The code computes ScheduleEnd =
I->getNextNode() and immediately asserts ScheduleEnd is non-null. In the
reproducer, the basic block contains an invoke instruction, which is a
terminator. If the algorithm attempts to extend past a terminator,
I->getNextNode() returns null and triggers the assertion.\n\n2. Analyzing
opt's Log:\nThe debug log shows the SLP pass first successfully schedules a
PHI bundle, and then it attempts to build and schedule a bundle around '%add
= add i32 0, 0' in block 'bb'. The scheduling region initialization and
dependence updates run until extendSchedulingRegion is called for this
scalar. The invocation crashes at the assertion 'ScheduleEnd && \"tried to
vectorize a terminator?\"'. This aligns with trying to extend the region end
across a terminator (invoke). The log confirms initialization at '%add' and
then the failure occurs immediately during scheduling that bundle.\n\n3.
Root Cause Analysis:\nextendSchedulingRegion assumes that, when extending
the region 'end' side, the instruction I we stop at is not the terminator,
so I->getNextNode() must be valid. In blocks ending with an invoke (which is
a terminator and also carries unwind edges), the iterator logic can lead to
choosing the terminator as I. As a result, I->getNextNode() is null and the
assertion fires. The rest of BlockScheduling code carefully treats
non-schedulable instructions (e.g., PHI, assume-like intrinsics), but it
lacks a guard against crossing or including terminators while extending the
region. The assertion message itself indicates the expected invariant: we
must never try to vectorize a terminator.\n\nGiven that the scheduling
region must never include the terminator, we need to ensure
extendSchedulingRegion bails out when I is a terminator, or otherwise clamps
ScheduleEnd to not advance past the final instruction.\n\n4. Proposed Edit
Point(s):\nEdit in llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp around
lines 21066-21073 to add a defensive guard preventing extension past
terminators and avoiding the null dereference/assert:\n\n- Before calling
initScheduleData and advancing ScheduleEnd, check if I is a terminator or if
I->getNextNode() is null. If so, return false (cannot extend the region end
past a terminator). This maintains the invariant and avoids asserting.\n-
Keep the assertion about being in the same parent block.\n\nConcrete
change:\n\nReplace:\n  assert(I->getParent() == ScheduleEnd->getParent()
&&\n         \"Instruction is in wrong basic block.\");\n
initScheduleData(ScheduleEnd, I->getNextNode(), LastLoadStoreInRegion,\n
nullptr);\n  ScheduleEnd = I->getNextNode();\n  assert(ScheduleEnd &&
\"tried to vectorize a terminator?\");\n  LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << \"SLP:
extend schedule region end to \" << *I << \"\\n\");\n  return
true;\n\nWith:\n  assert(I->getParent() == ScheduleEnd->getParent() &&\n
\"Instruction is in wrong basic block.\");\n  // Do not attempt to extend
past a terminator. getNextNode() is null there.\n  if (!I->getNextNode() ||
I->isTerminator()) {\n    LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << \"SLP:  cannot extend
schedule region end past terminator: \"\n                      << *I <<
\"\\n\");\n    return false;\n  }\n  initScheduleData(ScheduleEnd,
I->getNextNode(), LastLoadStoreInRegion,\n                   nullptr);\n
ScheduleEnd = I->getNextNode();\n  LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << \"SLP:  extend
schedule region end to \" << *I << \"\\n\");\n  return true;\n\nThis change
preserves the invariant and avoids the assert by refusing to extend when I
is the block terminator.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nThe crash is caused by
attempting to extend the scheduling region end over a terminator (invoke),
leading to a null next node and triggering the assertion. Adding a guard in
extendSchedulingRegion to bail out when encountering a terminator prevents
the vectorizer from trying to include terminators in its scheduling window.
This fix is conservative and aligns with the design intent expressed by the
assertion message, and will prevent the abort for the provided reproducer
and similar cases.",
